# Frameworks

Using Scalate with popular web frameworks

--- name:content pipeline:jade

There are lots of different (web) frameworks out there to suit all tastes and requirements.

.left
  :markdown
    # [Play](http://www.playframework.org/modules/scalate)
.right
  :markdown
    Scalate with the [Play framework](http://www.playframework.org/).  Play focuses on developer productivity and targets RESTful architectures.

.left
  :markdown
    # [Jog](jog.html)
.right
  :markdown
    Jog stands for JAXRS/[Jersey](https://jersey.dev.java.net/) on [Guice](http://code.google.com/p/google-guice/). [Jog](jog.html) is a 
    way of using Scalate with JAXRS for the RESTful controller layer along with [Guice](http://code.google.com/p/google-guice/) for dependency injection.

.left
  :markdown
    # [Lift](lift.html)
.right
  :markdown
    Scalate with the [Lift framework](http://liftweb.net/).  Lift is a popular Scala based web framework with particularly powerful Comet support.

.left
  :markdown
    # [Scalatra](scalatra.html)

.right
  :markdown
    [Scalatra](scalatra.html) is a tiny, [Sinatra](http://www.sinatrarb.com/)-like web framework for Scala

.left
  :markdown
    # [OSGi](osgi.html)

.right
  :markdown
    [OSGi](osgi.html) is a module system and service platform for the Java programming language, used by e.g. [Apache Karaf](http://karaf.apache.org)

.left
  :markdown
    # [Spring MVC](spring-mvc.html)

.right
  :markdown
    Scalate with the [Spring MVC framework](http://www.springsource.org/go-webflow2). Spring MVC is a flexible MVC web application framework, built on
    core [Spring](http://www.springsource.org/) functionality.

